---
/**
 * OrganizerGuide.astro — how to run a circle, on the page where you run it.
 *
 * English only, matching the rest of /admin. The member-facing FAQ is trilingual
 * because members read it; this is the operator's own screen.
 *
 * Written against what the code actually does, including two steps it does NOT yet
 * do. A guide that tells someone to click a button that is not there teaches them to
 * distrust the guide.
 */
import './OrganizerGuide.css';
---

<section class="og">
  <details class="og__wrap">
    <summary class="og__summary">
      <span class="og__chev" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
      <span class="og__title">Running a circle</span>
      <span class="og__sub">setup order, and what is not built yet</span>
    </summary>

    <div class="og__body">
      <p class="og__lede">
        Order matters here. A circle can only be arranged while it is <em>forming</em> —
        once the first round opens, the roster and the turn order are fixed for everyone,
        including you.
      </p>

      <ol class="og__steps">
        <li>
          <strong>Create the circle.</strong> Name it, set the amount each person puts in
          and how often. It starts as <em>forming</em>. A circle needs at least three
          members before it can start.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Put people in it.</strong> Drag them from “Waiting to be placed” onto the
          tin, on the Circles page. Anyone who has signed up but is not in a circle waits
          there.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Set the turn order.</strong> Drag the cards inside the tin. This is the
          order the group agreed, and it is the last chance to change it.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Give each person a payout wallet.</strong> That is where her turn gets
          paid. You can set it for her, or she can set her own once she has signed in.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Get each wallet proven.</strong> She sends a small amount from the wallet
          to itself; that proves she controls it. <strong>Two weeks from setting an
          address</strong> — after that her turn will not open until it is proven. Changing
          a wallet restarts the two weeks.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Send each person her link.</strong> Single use, expires in seven days. It
          binds her login to her place in the circle, so she arrives as herself.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Open round one.</strong> This ends forming. The roster locks, the turn
          order freezes, this round’s payout address is snapshotted so it cannot be swapped
          mid-round, and everyone except the recipient gets a payment due.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h3 class="og__h3">Add a second organizer on day one</h3>
      <p>
        Only an owner or admin can open a round. If you are unavailable, the circle stalls —
        nobody’s money is stuck, because it was never pooled, but the rounds stop advancing
        until someone with access opens them. Two people who can run it is the difference
        between a pause and a dead circle. The button is in your account menu, top right.
      </p>

      <h3 class="og__h3">What you cannot do, on purpose</h3>
      <ul class="og__list">
        <li>
          <strong>Move or remove anyone once a circle is running.</strong> Adding is an
          admission vote, removing is an expulsion vote. You can propose; the group decides.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>See anyone’s wallet balance.</strong> There is no code path to show one.
          You see what was agreed and what happened, never what she holds.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Rank or score anyone.</strong> The app shows facts, never a rating.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="og__h3">Not built yet — plan around these</h3>
      <ul class="og__list og__list--warn">
        <li>
          <strong>A brand new group cannot be created yet.</strong> Members come from the
          join flow, where someone names an existing circle and a sponsor — so the first
          members of a circle that has none cannot be added. Three friends starting today
          have no way in.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Payments are not observed.</strong> Opening a round creates a payment due
          for each member, and nothing marks them paid — no chain watcher exists yet. Until
          it does, a circle can run correctly and still show everyone as unpaid. Do not
          read that as anyone being late.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </details>
</section>
